Abstract

Federated learning (FL) aims to protect data privacy by cooperatively learning a model without sharing private data among users. For Federated Learning of Deep Neural Network with billions of model parameters, existing privacy-preserving solutions are unsatisfactory. Homomorphic encryption (HE) based methods provide secure privacy protections but suffer from extremely high computational and communication overheads rendering it almost useless in practice [14, 16, 32]. Deep learning with Differential Privacy (DP) [5] was implemented as a practical learning algorithm at a manageable cost in complexity[1]. However, DP is vulnerable to aggressive Bayesian restoration attacks as disclosed in the literature [12, 34, 35, 31] and demonstrated in experimental results of this work.

To address the aforementioned perplexity, we propose a novel Bayesian Privacy (BP) framework which enables Bayesian restoration attacks to be formulated as the probability of reconstructing private data from observed public information. Specifically, the proposed BP framework accurately quantifies privacy loss by Kullback-Leibler (KL) Divergence between the prior distribution about the privacy data and the posterior distribution of restoration private data conditioning on exposed information. To our best knowledge, this Bayesian Privacy analysis is the first to provides theoretical justification of secure privacy-preserving capabilities against Bayesian restoration attacks. As a concrete use case, we demonstrate that a novel federated deep learning method using private passport layers is able to simultaneously achieve high model performance, privacy-preserving capability and low computational complexity. Theoretical analysis is in accordance with empirical measurements of information leakage extensively experimented with a variety of DNN networks on image classification MNIST, CIFAR10, and CIFAR100 datasets.

1 Introduction

Since the introduction of Federated learning (FL) [20, 24], a variety of technologies have been adopted to improve the privacy-preserving capability and the model performance of FL process while maintaining computational complexity low. For instance, homomorphic encryption (HE) [14] provides secure protection of exchanged information and training data from being espied by semi-honest parties. However, extremely heavy computation and communication overhead incurred by HE make it unsuitable to protect Deep Neural Network (DNN) models which often consist of billions of model parameters. On the other hand, due to its low computational complexity, Differential Privacy (DP) [6] has been integrated into a practical DP-SGD algorithm to train deep neural networks with a modest privacy budget and at a manageable cost in complexity [1]. Nevertheless, privacy protection provided by randomization in DP is not as secure as that of HE. Even with significant random noise being added, attackers may still infer training data at pixel level accuracy by launching Bayesian restoration attacks including Deep Leakage [12, 34, 35, 31, 18] and model inversion attacks [11, 18].

To address aforementioned shortcomings of Homomorphic encryption and Differential Privacy, first, we propose to quantify privacy-preserving capability with a measurable Bayesian probability of reconstructing private data from observed public information. The proposed privacy loss, referred to as Bayesian Privacy (BP) loss, directly measures the removal of uncertainty about reconstructed private data, in terms of KL divergence between the posterior belief and the prior belief of private data. To out best knowledge, BP is the first work that takes into account two adversarial processes i.e. a protection mechanism and an attack method within a unified Bayesian framework. Our experiments shown that BP losses faithfully quantify information leakage incurred by Bayesian restoration attacks. Second, we propose a novel Federated Deep Learning with Private Passport (FDL-PP) protection mechanism to simultaneously achieve high model performance, privacy-preserving capability and low computational complexity. Using the Bayesian Privacy framework, we also provide theoretical justification that the proposed FDL-PP method is bound to defeat various Bayesian restoration attacks. Extensive experiments with image classification MNIST, CIFAR10 and CIFAR100 datasets is in accordance with theoretical analysis.

2 Related work

We review below related work from three aspects, namely, privacy definition, protection mechanism and privacy leakage attacks.

Privacy definition: (ϵ,δ)italic-ϵ𝛿(\epsilon,\delta)-Differential Privacy (DP) arose as a mathematically rigorous definition of privacy for data analysis [5, 6] and since then researchers proposed a number of DP variants including moments accountants suitable for deep learning [1], Gaussian Differential Privacy (GDP) with closed-form privacy bound and stronger guarantee [3] and Bayesian Differential Privacy (BDP) taking into account data distribution and achieving tighter privacy guarantees [28]111Bayesian Differential Privacy (BDP) is different from the proposed Bayesian Privacy (BP) in that BDP as a variant of DP cannot effectively defense Bayesian Restoration attacks, which are formulated in the proposed Bayesian Privacy framework (see the next section).

An alternative privacy definition due to [7] proposed to measure the privacy loss by the Kullback-Leibler (KL) Divergence between the prior belief and the posterior belief triggered by observed messages. We adopt this Bayesian Privacy (BP) analysis and generalize it as a unified framework to model both Bayesian restoration attacks and various protection mechanisms.

Protection mechanism: adding random noise to exchanged information i.e. randomization is the primary protection adopted by Differential Privacy and its variants. Despite of its simplicity and popularity, this approach inevitably leads to compromised performance in terms of slow convergence, low model performance and loose privacy guarantee as documented in [3, 28, 4] etc.. On the other hand, privacy protection provided by Homomorphic Encryption (HE) is in principle more secure than DP [14]. However, computational and communication overhead incurred by HE are orders of magnitude higher than that of randomization approach adopted in DP.

Split Learning (SL) in a federated setting [17] proposed to separate neural network architectures into private and public models, and to protect private models by hiding them from other parties. This protection is effective to some extent, yet, aggressive attackers may still infer private models and data through exposed public models (as demonstrated in our experiments).

Passport layers was used to modulate DNN outputs for the purpose of verifying ownership and intellectual property rights (IPR) of DNN models [8]. We propose to integrate passport layers in private models to further enhance privacy protection capabilities.

Privacy leakage attacks: it was understood that adversary of Differential Privacy seek to determine whether the observed outcome is due to one of two neighboring datasets differing by a single data point. While this hypothesis testing interpretation of Differential Privacy was elucidated in [29, 19, 21, 2, 3], it is limited by the neighboring datasets assumption and does not apply to aggressive gradient-based attacks recently proposed by [12, 34, 35, 31] and model inversion attacks in [11, 18]. These attacks follow the Bayesian restoration framework introduced in the present paper.

3 Bayesian Privacy

In this work we propose a privacy definition which is based on the notion of applying Bayesian restoration to recover original (training) data from public information exposed during the federated learning process. Hence, the proposed framework is referred to as Bayesian Privacy in this article. In a nutshell, Bayesian Privacy loss is quantified by Kullback-Leibler Divergence between the prior distribution about the privacy data and the posterior distribution of restoration private data conditioning on exposed information (see Definition 3 for details).

The Bayesian Privacy framework explicitly takes into account of two adversarial processes, namely protection mechanism and privacy leakage attacks, each of which has their respective goals. For the sake of privacy protection, the main concern is to prevent information about original data from being disclosed i.e. to provide strong privacy guarantee. The goal of privacy leakage attack, on the other hand, is to recovery original data from exposed information e.g. the updating of deep neural network models.

It must be noted that the modeling of these two adversarial tasks in the unified Bayesian Privacy framework is well-justified, since estimated privacy guarantee without considering leakage attacks are too loose to provide accurate accounts of information leakage. Indeed, the deficiency of Differential Privacy framework is such an example as documented in the literature [28, 3, 4] etc. and demonstrated by experimental results in the present paper.

3.1 Bayesian Privacy in Federated learning

In this work we consider a federated deep learning scenario, where K𝐾K participants collaboratively learn a multi-layered deep neural network model without exposing their private training data [24, 30]. We assume certain participants or the server might be semi-honest adversary, in the sense that they do not submit any malformed messages but may launch privacy attacks on exchanged information from other participants.

A single client has a private data x∈X𝑥𝑋x\in X and exposed public information 𝒢∈Ω𝒢Ω\mathcal{G}\in\Omega which is related to private data by a mapping 𝒢=g​(x)𝒢𝑔𝑥\mathcal{G}=g(x), X→Ω→𝑋ΩX\to\Omega. Note that the mapping g​()𝑔g() is assumed to be known to all participants in federated learning, while data x𝑥x is kept secret only to its owner. In case that g​()𝑔g() is an invertable function, it is straightforward for adversaries to infer data x=g−1​(𝒢)𝑥superscript𝑔1𝒢x=g^{-1}(\mathcal{G}) from the exposed information.

In general g​()𝑔g() is NOT invertable, for instance in the context of federated deep neural network learning, g​(x)𝑔𝑥g(x) is the exchanged neural network parameters or its gradients depending on input training data x𝑥x. For classification tasks, the NN model parameters 𝒢𝒢\mathcal{G} is sought by minimizing a loss function defined on training data x𝑥x:

𝒢∗=min𝒢⁡LC​E​(𝒢,x),superscript𝒢subscript𝒢subscript𝐿𝐶𝐸𝒢𝑥\begin{split}{\mathcal{G}}^{*}=\min\limits_{\mathcal{G}}L_{CE}(\mathcal{G},x),\end{split} (1)

in which L​()𝐿L() is often the cross-entropy (CE) loss for the classification task.

3.2 Protection Mechanism in Federated Learning

Definition 1.

A protection mechanism is a mapping 𝒢~=ℳ​(𝒢),Ω→Ωformulae-sequence~𝒢ℳ𝒢→ΩΩ\tilde{\mathcal{G}}=\mathcal{M}(\mathcal{G}),\Omega\to\Omega that takes as inputs exposed information 𝒢𝒢\mathcal{G} and outputs a modification of exposed information 𝒢~~𝒢\tilde{\mathcal{G}}.

Remark: in the literature there are various forms of protection mechanisms in federated learning including,

  • •

    Randomization adding a random perturbation to observed information 𝒢~=Randϵ​(𝒢)=𝒢+ϵ~𝒢subscriptRanditalic-ϵ𝒢𝒢italic-ϵ\tilde{\mathcal{G}}=\text{Rand}_{\epsilon}(\mathcal{G})=\mathcal{G}+\epsilon, where ϵitalic-ϵ\epsilon is additive noise or perturbation. For instance, Differential Privacy [15] adds additive noise following Gaussian or Laplacian distribution into model or gradients; Soteria [26] perturbs the output of hidden layer.

  • •

    Enforcing Sparsity of the observed information i.e. 𝒢~=Spar{s,t}​(𝒢)~𝒢subscriptSpar𝑠𝑡𝒢\tilde{\mathcal{G}}=\text{Spar}_{\{s,t\}}(\mathcal{G}). For instance, SplitFed[27] splits a neural network model into t𝑡t private and s𝑠s public layers and only exposes partial information (public layer); Model compression [35] prunes gradients that are below a threshold magnitude to leak the partial information of gradients.

  • •

    Modulating exposed information by adding private passport layers to DNN models, which is a novel protection mechanism parameterized by private passport P𝑃P and plays an indispensable role in the proposed FDL-PP method. The underlying optimization process is as follows:

    𝒢~=ModP​(𝒢)=arg​min𝒢⁡(LCE​(𝒢,x)+LP​(𝒢,P)),~𝒢subscriptMod𝑃𝒢subscriptargmin𝒢subscript𝐿CE𝒢𝑥subscript𝐿𝑃𝒢𝑃\begin{split}\tilde{\mathcal{G}}=\text{Mod}_{P}(\mathcal{G})=\operatorname*{arg\,min}\limits_{\mathcal{G}}\big{(}L_{\text{CE}}(\mathcal{G},x)+L_{P}(\mathcal{G},P)\big{)},\end{split} (2)

    in which 𝒢𝒢\mathcal{G} is model parameters in deep neural networks, P𝑃P is a private passport, LCE​(⋅)subscript𝐿CE⋅L_{\text{CE}}(\cdot) is the cross-entropy (CE) loss for classification task and LP​(𝒢,P)subscript𝐿𝑃𝒢𝑃L_{P}(\mathcal{G},P) is the regularization term to modulate 𝒢𝒢\mathcal{G} through the private passport P𝑃P (also see eq. (25) and text).

  • •

    Homomorphic Encryption (HE), which protects exposed information by secure encryption i.e. 𝒢~=Enc​(𝒢)~𝒢Enc𝒢\tilde{\mathcal{G}}=\text{Enc}(\mathcal{G}) [14].

It must be noted that different protection mechanisms can be used in combination to provide more secure protection e.g. by adopting both splitting and modulating protection in the proposed FDL-PP method. Different settings of protection methods affect not only privacy but also the model performance of federated deep neural network models as well as the complexity of learning process. The motivation of this research, as stated in Introduction section, is to seek appropriate protection mechanism that simultaneously achieves high privacy-preserving capability, model performance and low complexity.

3.4 Bayesian Privacy with Adversarial Process

Definition 3.

Given a protection mechanism ℳℳ\mathcal{M}, a privacy leakage attack 𝒜𝒜\mathcal{A} and a prior knowledge distribution F0subscript𝐹0F_{0} about private data x𝑥x, the Bayesian Privacy (BP) is defined by:

𝐁𝐏(ℳ,𝒜,g,F0)=KL(F0∥F𝒜(x~|ℳ(g(x)))),\mathbf{BP}\big{(}\mathcal{M},\mathcal{A},g,F_{0}\big{)}=\textbf{KL}\Big{(}F_{0}\|F_{\mathcal{A}}\big{(}\tilde{x}|\mathcal{M}(g(x))\big{)}\Big{)}, (8)

in which KL denotes the Kullback-Leibler Divergence between the prior knowledge distribution F0subscript𝐹0F_{0} and the posterior distribution F𝒜subscript𝐹𝒜F_{\mathcal{A}} conditioning on exposed information. Depending on different prior knowledge F0subscript𝐹0F_{0}, there are two cases following the definition:

In this case, attacks aim to get a high KL values with the large knowledge increment while clients want to derive a low KL values to protect data privacy as follows,

    Consequently, we define the 𝐁𝐏𝐊𝐈=𝐁𝐏​(ℳ,𝒜,g,F0¯)subscript𝐁𝐏𝐊𝐈𝐁𝐏ℳ𝒜𝑔¯subscript𝐹0\mathbf{BP_{KI}}=\mathbf{BP}(\mathcal{M},\mathcal{A},g,\bar{F_{0}}) as Bayesian Privacy Knowledge Increment given the prior knowledge. For any protection and attack method, we adopt 𝐁𝐏𝐊𝐈subscript𝐁𝐏𝐊𝐈\mathbf{BP_{KI}} measure to quantify privacy leakage loss of the protection mechanism ℳℳ\mathcal{M} against the attacking method 𝒜𝒜\mathcal{A} with experimental results presented in the following section.
    Remark: If the attackers have no knowledge at first, they only randomly guess the original input, which cause the large uncertainty. They want to be sure that the restored data based on observed information is accurate instead of guessing. Specifically, adversaries want to restore the same result with multiple attacks. Some attacks in federated learning [31] borrows similar idea to increase the successful rate of attack by minimizing the uncertainty of restored data with multiple attack.

    𝐊𝐋(Fx∗||Fx~)=𝔼x∈Px∗​log⁡Px∗Px~=𝔼x∈Px∗​log⁡P(x∗|x~)=−log⁡12​π​σ2+12​σ2​𝔼x∈Px∗​(x~−x∗)2\begin{split}\mathbf{KL}(F_{x^{*}}||F_{\tilde{x}})=&\mathbb{E}_{x\in P_{x^{*}}}\log\frac{P_{x^{*}}}{P_{\tilde{x}}}=\mathbb{E}_{x\in P_{x^{*}}}\log P_{(x^{*}|\tilde{x})}\\ &=-\log\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma^{2}}}+\frac{1}{2\sigma^{2}}\mathbb{E}_{x\in P_{x^{*}}}(\tilde{x}-x^{*})^{2}\end{split} (11)

    where x~=𝒜​(ℳ​(g​(x∗)))~𝑥𝒜ℳ𝑔superscript𝑥\tilde{x}=\mathcal{A}(\mathcal{M}(g(x^{*}))).

It must be noted that the two adversary processes protection and attacking in eq. (9,10) are taken separately by clients and attackers of federated learning respectively. The proposed Bayesian Privacy aims to provides accurate estimates of both processes within a unified framework. This theoretical analysis is in accordance with the empirical study as illustrated in the main paper and Appendix E.

4 Federated Deep Learning with Private Passport

This section illustrates the proposed privacy-preserving Federated Deep Learning with Private Passport (FDL-PP) and provides theoretical proof that private passport is robust against reconstruction attacks.

4.1 FDL-PP Algorithm

Consider a neural network Φ​(x;w,b):X→R:Φ𝑥𝑤𝑏→𝑋𝑅\Phi(x;w,b):X\to R, where x∈X𝑥𝑋x\in X, w𝑤w and b𝑏b are the weights and biases of neural networks, and C𝐶C is the output dimension. In the machine learning task, we aim to optimize w𝑤w and b𝑏b of network according to loss L​(Φ​(x;w,b))𝐿Φ𝑥𝑤𝑏L(\Phi(x;w,b)), where x𝑥x is the input data and y𝑦y is the ground truth label.

Inspired by [27], we separate a deep neural network into several public (ϕitalic-ϕ\phi) and private layers (ψ𝜓\psi) as the shown in Fig. 1 and the following equation:

Φ(x;w,b)=ϕ[1]∘ϕ[2]∘⋅∘ϕ[s]∘ψ[1]∘ψ[2]⋯ψ[t](x),\Phi(x;w,b)=\phi^{[1]}\circ\phi^{[2]}\circ\cdot\circ\phi^{[s]}\circ\psi^{[1]}\circ\psi^{[2]}\cdots\psi^{[t]}(x), (12)

where s𝑠s, t𝑡t are, respectively, the numbers of public and private layers. Noticeably, parameters in private layers are kept secret to preserve data privacy and parameters in public layers are shared without encryption.

Splitting models allows private model parameters to be kept secret, yet, training data can still be inferred from the public parameters as proved by Theorem 1. We therefore further enhance the privacy preserving capability by adopting a private passport layer approach proposed by [8, 33] to protect DNN models. For each private convolution layer, a private passport layer consisting of a fully connected autoencoder (Encoder E𝐸E and Decoder D𝐷D) and average pooling layer is used to derive the crucial normalization parameters γ,β𝛾𝛽\gamma,\beta. Note that private passports are used to compute these parameters as follows:

𝐎l​(𝐗p)=γl​(𝐖pl∗𝐗cl)+βl,γl=Avg​(𝐃​(𝐄​(𝐖pl∗𝐏γl)))βl=Avg​(𝐃​(𝐄​(𝐖pl∗𝐏βl)))formulae-sequencesuperscript𝐎𝑙subscript𝐗𝑝superscript𝛾𝑙superscriptsubscript𝐖𝑝𝑙superscriptsubscript𝐗𝑐𝑙superscript𝛽𝑙superscript𝛾𝑙Avg𝐃𝐄superscriptsubscript𝐖𝑝𝑙superscriptsubscript𝐏𝛾𝑙superscript𝛽𝑙Avg𝐃𝐄superscriptsubscript𝐖𝑝𝑙superscriptsubscript𝐏𝛽𝑙\begin{split}\mathbf{O}^{l}(\mathbf{X}_{p})=&\gamma^{l}(\mathbf{W}_{p}^{l}*\mathbf{X}_{c}^{l})+\beta^{l},\\ \gamma^{l}=&\text{Avg}\Big{(}\mathbf{D}\big{(}\mathbf{E}(\mathbf{W}_{p}^{l}*\mathbf{P}_{\gamma}^{l})\big{)}\Big{)}\\ \beta^{l}=&\text{Avg}\Big{(}\mathbf{D}\big{(}\mathbf{E}(\mathbf{W}_{p}^{l}*\mathbf{P}_{\beta}^{l})\big{)}\Big{)}\end{split} (13)

where * denotes the convolution operations, l𝑙l is the layer number, 𝐗csubscript𝐗𝑐\mathbf{X}_{c} is the private data fed to the convolution layer. 𝐎​()𝐎\mathbf{O}() is the corresponding linear transformation of outputs, while 𝐏γlsubscriptsuperscript𝐏𝑙𝛾\mathbf{P}^{l}_{\gamma} and 𝐏βlsubscriptsuperscript𝐏𝑙𝛽\mathbf{P}^{l}_{\beta} are passports private to each client used to derive scale factor γ𝛾\gamma and bias term β𝛽\beta respectively.

The right part of Fig. 1 illustrates the procedure of passport embedding. Since both the private layer parameters and passport are kept secret, it is impossible for adversary to infer training data from the private layers’ outputs. In addition, we observe the sparsity of weights after embedding passport, which prevents attackers to restore the training data (see proof in Theorem 1)

The training procedure of FDL-PP is illustrated in following three steps (shown in Algorithm 1):

  • •

    Firstly, all clients carry out the forward and backward propagation on a global model in parallel and upload their public layers of the model to the server;

  • •

    Secondly, the central server process the FederatedAverage [24] of the public layers and update;

  • •

    Finally, clients download the updated public model, followed by back-propagation and updating to their private layers with embedding the passport.

4.2 Analysis of Privacy Preserving with Private Passport

Consider a neural network Ψ​(x;w,b,w~,b~):ϕ∘ψ​(x):Ψ𝑥𝑤𝑏~𝑤~𝑏italic-ϕ𝜓𝑥\Psi(x;w,b,\tilde{w},\tilde{b}):\phi\circ\psi(x) including one public (ϕitalic-ϕ\phi) and one private layer ψ𝜓\psi as Def. 4, where x∈𝕏𝑥𝕏x\in\mathbb{X}, defining a mapping from 𝕏𝕏\mathbb{X} to Rcsuperscript𝑅𝑐R^{c}, c is output dimension. In the neural network, we optimize w𝑤w,b𝑏b through a loss function L​(Ψ​(x;w,b,w~,b~),y)𝐿Ψ𝑥𝑤𝑏~𝑤~𝑏𝑦L(\Psi(x;w,b,\tilde{w},\tilde{b}),y), where x𝑥x is input data, y𝑦y is ground truth labels.

    For private layer: O=ψ​(x)=a​(Dγ⋅w⋅x+b)𝑂𝜓𝑥𝑎⋅subscript𝐷𝛾𝑤𝑥𝑏O=\psi(x)=a(D_{\gamma}\cdot w\cdot x+b).

where a𝑎a is activation function; w𝑤w, w^^𝑤\hat{w} are 2D matrix of fully-connected weights of private and public layer; b𝑏b, b^^𝑏\hat{b} are bias vector; Dγsubscript𝐷𝛾D_{\gamma}, Dγ^^subscript𝐷𝛾\hat{D_{\gamma}} are diagonal matrix of scaling weights of batch normalization or passport layer; μ𝜇\mu, O𝑂O are the outputs of public and private layer; ⋅⋅\cdot denotes matrix product.

Remark: Any convolution layers can be converted into a fully-connected layer by simply stacking together spatially shifted convolution kernels ([23]). In addition, the scaling factor γ𝛾\gamma of batch normalization or passport layer could be explained by a diagonal matrix in the forward function. Consequently, we use a​(Dγ⋅w⋅x+b)𝑎⋅subscript𝐷𝛾𝑤𝑥𝑏a(D_{\gamma}\cdot w\cdot x+b) as forward function of private layer.

In the federated learning, the models or gradients of the public layers are leaked to server and other clients while are not leaked for private layers. Semi-honest adversary participants or the server aims to restore x𝑥x. Theoretical analysis of privacy-preserving capabilities concerns two aspects: (1) it is easy for attackers to restore the similar input compared to original input even if the private layers are not known in the SplitFed; (2) embedding passport into the private layers prevents the attackers to restore the original data.

5 Experimental Results

This section illustrates empirical evaluation of the proposed privacy-preserving method (FDL-PP) against existing solutions using the proposed Bayesian Privacy framework and experimental verification for the assumptions of Theorem 1.

5.1 Experiment Setup and Evaluation Metric

We investigate image classification problems on three datasets i.e. MNIST, CIFRA10 and CIFAR100 by utilizing three backbone networks (LeNet, AlexNet and ResNet-18). All experiments settings are briefly summarized as follows and elaborated in Appendix.

Methods: we compare the proposed FDL-PP method against four existing federated deep learning methods, namely, Distributed Deep Learning without privacy protection (DL) [24], Deep Learning with Differential Privacy (DLDP) [1] applying into federated learning [15], SplitFed [17, 27] and Federated Deep Learning with two Homomorphic Encryption variants CryptoNet [16] and BatchCrypt [32]. Note that there are two variants of DLDP method i.e. DLDP-A and DLDP-B respectively corresponding to small (σ=0.002𝜎0.002\sigma=0.002) and large (σ=0.128𝜎0.128\sigma=0.128) Gaussian noise added. The proposed FDL-PP method is implemented by splitting three backbone networks, keeping the first convolution and activation layers as the private layer, the rest layers as the public layer. The passport layer is appended after the private layer. See Fig. 1 and Algorithm 1 for method details.

Evaluation metrics: we compare model performances of different methods using classification actuaries on testing dataset. For learning complexity we report elapse time in seconds for one epoch of each learning method.

For privacy-preserving capabilities, we adopt the proposed Bayesian Privacy (𝐁𝐏𝐊𝐈subscript𝐁𝐏𝐊𝐈\mathbf{BP_{KI}} and 𝐁𝐏𝐌𝐒𝐄subscript𝐁𝐏𝐌𝐒𝐄\mathbf{BP_{MSE}}) defined by Def. 3. In particular, two attacking methods i.e. Deep leakage attack:DLG( [35] as one of the gradient-based attack and Model Inversion attack:MI [18] were employed 10 times to attack different learning methods. Corresponding Bayesian Privacy (𝐁𝐏𝐊𝐈subscript𝐁𝐏𝐊𝐈\mathbf{BP_{KI}} and 𝐁𝐏𝐌𝐒𝐄subscript𝐁𝐏𝐌𝐒𝐄\mathbf{BP_{MSE}}) were computed using the posterior distribution of restored private data.

5.2 Comparison of Privacy Preserving Mechanisms

Table 1 compares model performances, privacy-preserving capabilities in terms of Bayesian Privacy measured by both 𝐁𝐏𝐊𝐈subscript𝐁𝐏𝐊𝐈\mathbf{BP_{KI}} and 𝐁𝐏𝐌𝐒𝐄subscript𝐁𝐏𝐌𝐒𝐄\mathbf{BP_{MSE}}, and protection method complexity in terms of elapse time (s) for different protection methods. Model performances (accuracies) reported in BOLD are those with performances drop less than 1.5% w.r.t. the best performance. Bayesian Privacy Guarantees reported in BOLD are those with restoration error (𝐁𝐏𝐌𝐒𝐄subscript𝐁𝐏𝐌𝐒𝐄\mathbf{BP_{MSE}}) more than 0.05, ensuring sufficient privacy-preserving capabilities (see Fig. 2 for example restored images). Bayesian Privacy losses reported in BOLD are those with restored data distribution similar to random distribution (with KL divergence no more than 0.3). For training time reported in BOLD are those less than 100 seconds per epoch.

It was observed that Bayesian Privacy guarantee (by MSE) faithfully reflected the quality of training images reconstructed by two attacking methods, regardless of different protection methods i.e. DLDP, SplitFed and FDL-PP being employed. Fig. 2 shows example ground truth training images, corresponding reconstructed images and Bayesian Privacy measures. Bayesian Privacy leakages also provides accurate estimations of information leaked from the reconstructed images, without using ground truth images.

It must be noted that, unlike the proposed Bayesian Privacy, Differential Privacy loss estimated by either the strong composition Theorem or moments accountants turn out to be too loose and unpractical in the face of two restoration attacks employed in experiments. For instance, in Fig. 2, the DLDP-A protection was unable to defeat Deep Leakage and Model inversion attacks whereas restored images were almost identical to the original image. In this case, Bayesian Privacy guarantee (BPMSEsubscriptBPMSE\text{BP}_{\text{MSE}}) measured as low as 1.4​e-​61.4e-61.4\text{e-}6 and 3.0​e-​33.0e-33.0\text{e-}3 respectively. However, Differential Privacy still reported an acceptable level of privacy loss at (15.8,10−515.8superscript10515.8,10^{-5})-differential privacy with Gaussian noise (σ=0.002𝜎0.002\sigma=0.002) being added [1].

The proposed FDL-PP method outperformed DL, DLDP-A and SplitFed in terms of Bayesian Privacy guarantee (MSE) by a margin of 0.05 or more. On the other hand, FDL-PP achieved high model accuracy comparable to that of DL with classification accuracy drop around 0.2%, 1.2% and 0.3% tested for MNIST, CIFAR10 and CIFAR100 datasets respectively. In terms of computational complexity, FDL-PP took only 55 seconds elapse time per epoch. In contrast, the running time of Homomorphic Encryption based CryptoNet [16] was orders of magnitudes higher than alternative protection approaches. Even with efficient improvements adopted for the BatchCrypt method [32], the running time was still twice as high as that of the proposed FDL-PP and at the cost of degraded model accuracy about 14% lower for CIFAR10 classification. Among all methods compared in Table 1 and Fig 3, the proposed FDL-PP is the only protection method that simultaneously demonstrated satisfactory model performance, privacy preserving capabilities and low computational complexity. Advantages of the proposed FDL-PP is also illustrated in Fig. 3, in which FDL-PP is positioned on the top-right corner signalling simultaneous high model performances and privacy-preserving capabilities.

5.3 Empirical study of FDL-PP

This section illustrates empirical justifications of three assumptions used in Theorem 1 about the privacy-preserving capability of FDL-PP algorithm.

Assumption 1: Convergence of private weights (W𝑊W)
In the case 1 of the Theorem 1 (without passport), the Privacy Guarantees (B​PM​S​E𝐵subscript𝑃𝑀𝑆𝐸BP_{MSE}) is limited by ‖W−W~‖2subscriptnorm𝑊~𝑊2||W-\tilde{W}||_{2}, i.e. the difference of private weights between different clients. If ‖W−W~‖2subscriptnorm𝑊~𝑊2||W-\tilde{W}||_{2} decreases, the Privacy Guarantee is bounded from above by a small value.

The Fig.4 shows the change of average weights distance of private layer of different clients (∑i,j=1N‖Wi−Wj‖22/N2superscriptsubscript𝑖𝑗1𝑁superscriptsubscriptnormsubscript𝑊𝑖subscript𝑊𝑗22superscript𝑁2\sum\limits_{i,j=1}^{N}||W_{i}-W_{j}||_{2}^{2}/N^{2}), where Wisubscript𝑊𝑖W_{i} is private layer weight of it​hsubscript𝑖𝑡ℎi_{th} client) in CIFAR10 during the training. It illustrates the difference of private weights among different clients decreases from 0.14 to 0.01 during training. Therefore, it is easy for attackers to restore the similar original input provided by the small Privacy Guarantee.

Assumption 2: the rank of private weights decreases
The case 2 of the Theorem 1 (embedding passport) has one assumption that the rank of private layer weights decreases if the passport is used. The left figure of Fig. 5 shows the rank of private weights decreases from 55 to 37, which verifies our assumption is reasonable.
Remark: For the 2D matrix W𝑊W, we take singular value decomposition of the W𝑊W and choose the 99%​∑percent9999\%\sum(singular value) as threshold τ𝜏\tau. Finally, we use the number of singular values, which is larger than threshold, as the rank of W𝑊W.

Assumption 3: the norm of scaling factor decreases
In the case 2 of the Theorem 1 (embedding passport), the Privacy Guarantees (B​PM​S​E𝐵subscript𝑃𝑀𝑆𝐸BP_{MSE}) has a lower bound C‖Dγ‖2+‖Dγ~‖2𝐶subscriptnormsubscript𝐷𝛾2subscriptnorm~subscript𝐷𝛾2\frac{C}{||D_{\gamma}||_{2}+||\tilde{D_{\gamma}}||_{2}}.

The right figure of Fig.5 demonstrates the scaling factor decreases from 1 to less than 0.005 after embedding passport. Therefore, the lower bound of eq. 21 increases a lot, which provides a strong Bayesian Privacy Guarantee.

6 Conclusion

Recently proposed privacy attacks posed serious challenges to federated deep learning, in this work we proposed to reformulate the privacy definition from the lens of Bayesian data restoration and derived a rigorous Bayesian Privacy measure to quantify privacy leakage incurred by restored data. It was shown that estimated Bayesian Privacy leakages provided consistent accounts of the quality of restored images, and allowed us to investigate on the same ground a variety of protection mechanisms including randomization used in Differential Privacy. Bayesian Privacy based theoretical analysis of different protection mechanisms constitute the first contribution of our work.

Our second contribution lies in a novel passport-layer based protection method. Due to the private passports fed to private passport layers in each client, private data can no longer be restored from exchanged information (see Theorem 1). Consequently, public neural network model parameters can be exchanged without encryption saving a great deal of computational complexity. This simple approach manifested itself, in extensive experiments with MNIST, CIFAR10 and CIFAR100 classifications, as a practical solution that simultaneously meets all three requirements in secure privacy protection, high model performance and low complexity.

As for future work, we expect to investigate more protection and attacking methods in the generic Bayesian Privacy framework. In particular, to study adversarial protection methods that are aware of restoration attacks is one fruitful direction to explore further.

A.1 Experiment Setting

This section illustrates the experiment settings of the empirical study on our Federated learning framework with Bayesian Privacy.

A.1.1 DNN Model Architectures

The deep neural network architectures we investigated include the well-known AlexNet and ResNet-18. Private Passports 𝐏=(𝐏γ,𝐏β)𝐏subscript𝐏𝛾subscript𝐏𝛽\mathbf{P}=(\mathbf{P}_{\gamma},\mathbf{P}_{\beta}) are embedded into private convolution layers to derive crucial normalization scale weights 𝐖γsuperscript𝐖𝛾\mathbf{W}^{\gamma} and shifting factor 𝐖βsuperscript𝐖𝛽\mathbf{W}^{\beta} in LeNet, AlexNet and ResNet-18. Table 2 shows the detailed model architectures and parameter shape of LeNet, AlexNet and ResNet-18, which we employed in all the experiments.

A.1.2 Dataset

We evaluate classification tasks on standard MNIST, CIFAR10 and CIFAR100 dataset. The MNIST database of 10-class handwritten digits, has a training set of 60,000 examples, and a test set of 10,000 examples, CIFAR10 dataset consists of 60000 32x32 colour images in 10 classes, with 6000 images per class. CIFAR100 has 100 classes containing 600 images each. Respectively, we conduct stand image classification tasks of MNIST,CIFAR10 and CIFAR100 with LeNet, AlexNet and ResNet-18. We split the dataset into independently identically distribution (IID) setting for clients in horizontal federated learning experiments.

A.1.3 FL Setting

We simulate a K=10𝐾10K=10 clients horizontal federated learning system in a stand-alone machine with 8 Tesla V100-SXM2 32 GB GPUs and 72 cores of Intel(R) Xeon(R) Gold 61xx CPUs.

The clients update the weight updates, server adopts Fedavg[24] algorithm in to aggregate the model updates. The detailed experiment Hyper parameters we employ to conduct our federated learning are listed in the Table 3.

A.2 Attack Algorithm

We implement image restoration attack algorithms including Deep Leakage Attack and Model Inversion Attack. This section illustrates the algorithm implementation details of two type of attacks on Federated learning framework.

A.2.1 Deep Leakage Attack:

Deep leakage attack(DLG)[35] is implemented in the white box manner, server reconstructs client’s private data only according to the federated model W𝑊W and gradients ∇W∇𝑊\nabla W sent by clients. We refer to the source code in https://github.com/mit-han-lab/dlg and implement algorithm as shown in Alg. 2. The parameters of DLG attack please refer to Table 4

A.2.2 Model Inversion Attack:

Model Inversion Attack(MIA)[18] is implemented in the black-box setting of federated learning, that server S𝑆S conspires with client C1subscript𝐶1C_{1} to attack the private data of client C0subscript𝐶0C_{0}, the algorithm is implemented as Alg. 3.

A.3 Privacy Preserving Algorithm

We implement privacy-preserving FL algorithms including Differential Privacy, SplitFed and FDL-PP. This section illustrates the algorithm implementation details of our privacy preserving algorithm.

A.3.1 Federated Learning with Differential Privacy

We implement Differential Privacy(DP)[5] from the client’s local perspective: during each local training round, each local client adds Gaussian noise[15] to the network weight updates before broadcasting to the central server.

The Gaussian noise we adopt obeys Gaussian distribution 𝒩​(μ,σ2)𝒩𝜇superscript𝜎2\mathcal{N}(\mu,\sigma^{2}), we refer to the source code in https://github.com/cyrusgeyer/DiffPrivate˙FedLearning, and implement algorithm as shown in Alg. 4.

A.3.2 Splitfed with Passport

Consider a neural network Φ​(x;w,b):X→R:Φ𝑥𝑤𝑏→𝑋𝑅\Phi(x;w,b):X\to R, where x∈X𝑥𝑋x\in X, w𝑤w and b𝑏b are the weights and biases of neural networks, and C𝐶C is the output dimension. In the machine learning task, we aim to optimize w𝑤w and b𝑏b of network according to loss L​(Φ​(x;w,b))𝐿Φ𝑥𝑤𝑏L(\Phi(x;w,b)), where x𝑥x is the input data and y𝑦y is the ground truth label.

Inspired by [27], we separate a deep neural network into several public and private layers as the shown in the following equation:

Φ(x;w,b)=ϕ[1]∘ϕ[2]∘⋅∘ϕ[s]∘ψ[1]∘ψ[2]⋯ψ[t](x),\Phi(x;w,b)=\phi^{[1]}\circ\phi^{[2]}\circ\cdot\circ\phi^{[s]}\circ\psi^{[1]}\circ\psi^{[2]}\cdots\psi^{[t]}(x), (23)

where s𝑠s, t𝑡t are, respectively, the numbers of public and private layers.

We therefore further enhance the privacy preserving capability by adopting a private passport layer approach proposed by [9, 33] to protect DNN models. For each private convolution layer, a private passport layer consisting of a fully connected auto encoder (Encoder E𝐸E and Decoder D𝐷D) and average pooling layer is used to derive the crucial normalization parameters γ,β𝛾𝛽\gamma,\beta. Note that private passports are used to compute these parameters as follows:

𝐎l​(𝐗p)=γl​(𝐖pl∗𝐗cl)+βl,γl=Avg​(𝐃​(𝐄​(𝐖pl∗𝐏γl)))βl=Avg​(𝐃​(𝐄​(𝐖pl∗𝐏βl)))formulae-sequencesuperscript𝐎𝑙subscript𝐗𝑝superscript𝛾𝑙superscriptsubscript𝐖𝑝𝑙superscriptsubscript𝐗𝑐𝑙superscript𝛽𝑙superscript𝛾𝑙Avg𝐃𝐄superscriptsubscript𝐖𝑝𝑙superscriptsubscript𝐏𝛾𝑙superscript𝛽𝑙Avg𝐃𝐄superscriptsubscript𝐖𝑝𝑙superscriptsubscript𝐏𝛽𝑙\begin{split}\mathbf{O}^{l}(\mathbf{X}_{p})=&\gamma^{l}(\mathbf{W}_{p}^{l}*\mathbf{X}_{c}^{l})+\beta^{l},\\ \gamma^{l}=&\text{Avg}\Big{(}\mathbf{D}\big{(}\mathbf{E}(\mathbf{W}_{p}^{l}*\mathbf{P}_{\gamma}^{l})\big{)}\Big{)}\\ \beta^{l}=&\text{Avg}\Big{(}\mathbf{D}\big{(}\mathbf{E}(\mathbf{W}_{p}^{l}*\mathbf{P}_{\beta}^{l})\big{)}\Big{)}\end{split} (24)

where * denotes the convolution operations, l𝑙l is the layer number, 𝐗csubscript𝐗𝑐\mathbf{X}_{c} is the private data fed to the convolution layer. 𝐎​()𝐎\mathbf{O}() is the corresponding linear transformation of outputs, while 𝐏γlsubscriptsuperscript𝐏𝑙𝛾\mathbf{P}^{l}_{\gamma} and 𝐏βlsubscriptsuperscript𝐏𝑙𝛽\mathbf{P}^{l}_{\beta} are passports private to each client used to derive scale factor γ𝛾\gamma and bias term β𝛽\beta respectively.

Scale factor γ𝛾\gamma and bias term β𝛽\beta are enforced to take values depending on passports 𝐏γlsubscriptsuperscript𝐏𝑙𝛾\mathbf{P}^{l}_{\gamma} and 𝐏βlsubscriptsuperscript𝐏𝑙𝛽\mathbf{P}^{l}_{\beta} and this constraint can be succinctly represented by a regularization term to be minimized as follows:

LP​(w,P):=‖γl−Avg​(𝐃​(𝐄​(𝐖pl∗𝐏γl)))‖2+‖βl−Avg​(𝐃​(𝐄​(𝐖pl∗𝐏βl)))‖2,assignsubscript𝐿𝑃𝑤𝑃subscriptdelimited-∥∥superscript𝛾𝑙Avg𝐃𝐄superscriptsubscript𝐖𝑝𝑙superscriptsubscript𝐏𝛾𝑙2subscriptdelimited-∥∥superscript𝛽𝑙Avg𝐃𝐄superscriptsubscript𝐖𝑝𝑙superscriptsubscript𝐏𝛽𝑙2\begin{split}L_{P}(w,P):=&\|\gamma^{l}-\text{Avg}\Big{(}\mathbf{D}\big{(}\mathbf{E}(\mathbf{W}_{p}^{l}*\mathbf{P}_{\gamma}^{l})\big{)}\Big{)}\|_{2}+\\ &\|\beta^{l}-\text{Avg}\Big{(}\mathbf{D}\big{(}\mathbf{E}(\mathbf{W}_{p}^{l}*\mathbf{P}_{\beta}^{l})\big{)}\Big{)}\|_{2},\end{split} (25)

in which w={𝐖pl,γl,βl}𝑤superscriptsubscript𝐖𝑝𝑙superscript𝛾𝑙superscript𝛽𝑙w=\{\mathbf{W}_{p}^{l},\gamma^{l},\beta^{l}\} is the neural network model parameters and P={𝐏γl,𝐏βl}𝑃superscriptsubscript𝐏𝛾𝑙superscriptsubscript𝐏𝛽𝑙P=\{\mathbf{P}_{\gamma}^{l},\mathbf{P}_{\beta}^{l}\} the passport for brevity.

Combined with the cross-entropy loss for the classification task, the NN model parameters w={𝐖pl,γl,βl}𝑤superscriptsubscript𝐖𝑝𝑙superscript𝛾𝑙superscript𝛽𝑙w=\{\mathbf{W}_{p}^{l},\gamma^{l},\beta^{l}\} are therefore sought by minimizing the following loss:

LFP(w,x,P)=LC​E(w,x)+LP(w,P),w∗=arg​minw⁡LFP​(w,x,P),formulae-sequencesubscript𝐿FP𝑤𝑥𝑃subscript𝐿𝐶𝐸𝑤𝑥subscript𝐿𝑃𝑤𝑃superscript𝑤subscriptargmin𝑤subscript𝐿FP𝑤𝑥𝑃\begin{split}L_{\text{FP}}(&w,x,P)=L_{CE}(w,x)+L_{P}(w,P),\\ &w^{*}=\operatorname*{arg\,min}_{w}L_{\text{FP}}(w,x,P),\end{split} (26)

in which x𝑥x is the given training data and P𝑃P the passport defined above.

It must be noted that the regularization term LP​(w,P)subscript𝐿𝑃𝑤𝑃L_{P}(w,P) enforces the scale and bias term {γ,β}𝛾𝛽\{\gamma,\beta\} and w𝑤w to take specific values that depend on not only the training data but also the passport. It is this modulation of NN parameters w𝑤w through the passport P𝑃P that plays an indispensable role in protecting the private model parameters and training data from being disclosed by restoration attacks (see detailed analysis in Appendix B, C and D).

The training procedure of FDL-PP is illustrated in following three steps (shown in Algorithm 1):

  • •

    Firstly, all clients carry out the forward and backward propagation on a global model in parallel and upload their public layers of the model to the server;

  • •

    Secondly, the central server process the FederatedAverage [24] of the public layers and update;

  • •

    Finally, clients download the updated public model, followed by back-propagation and updating to their private layers with embedding the passport.

A.4 Privacy Metrics

For each images including the original images and reconstructed images, we firstly scale the original images and reconstructed images to the range (0,1). For Bayesian Privacy guarantee, we calculate the mean square error between the original images and reconstructed images. For Bayesian Privacy loss, we statistics the numbers of pixel value of images in k intervals (ik,i+1k𝑖𝑘𝑖1𝑘\frac{i}{k},\frac{i+1}{k}, 0≤i≤k−10𝑖𝑘10\leq i\leq k-1) as the distribution of reconstructed images, and view the uniform distribution as the distribution of no prior. The KL distance between these two distributions are the Bayesian Privacy loss.
